Fig. S3 showed the cross-sectional SEM images of WP, 0.5ACDs/WP, 0.5LCDs/WP, and 1.0LCDs/WP coatings at different magnifications. Upon incorporating 0.5 wt% LCDs into WP, the fracture surface of the 0.5LCDs/WP coating (Fig. S3c) displayed increased smoothness without defects compared to the WP and 0.5ACDs/WP coating. This improvement could be attributed to the existence of hydroxyl, amino, sulfhydryl, and carboxyl groups on the surface of LCDs to establish hydrogen bonds and covalent bonds with epoxy matrix [16]. However, when the addition of LCDs was continuously increased to 1.0%, it would cause noticeable aggregation and undesirable defects (Fig. S3d
3). DSC tests (Fig. S4
) showed that the Tg values of WP, 0.5ACDs/WP, 0.5LCDs/WP, and 1.0LCDs/WP coatings were 67.0 °C, 80.8 °C, 83.9 °C, and 81.8 °C, respectively. The increasing in Tg also meant that the introduction of CDs could facilitate the increasing of the cross-linking density of the CDs/WP composite coating.
